{"role":"tool","content":"[CollectionName]\nextract\n\n[CollectionDescription]\nKQL examples and syntax documentation for extract use case. Includes query examples and relevant operators, functions, and syntax patterns for extract operations.\n\n[CollectionContent]\nFew-Shot Examples\n==================\nUser Prompt: Parse the metric1 param from the myMetrics field\nDataset Information: [{\"id\":\"myDataset\",\"provider\":\"S3\"}]\nGenerated KQL Query: cribl dataset=myDataset | extract source=myMetrics type=regex @'metric1=(?<foo>\\d+)'\n\n---\n\n\nKQL Syntax Documentation\n=========================\n\nBasics of Cribl Syntax\n----------------------\nThe Cribl Search Query Language is based on Microsoft's Kusto Query Language (KQL). A Cribl Search Query is a read-only request expressed in plain text that processes data and returns results in a tabular or graphical format. It consists of one or more query statements. Predominant type of query statement in a tabular expression statement. In a tabular expression statement, both input and output consists of tables or datasets. Think of a dataset as a definition that describes WHAT we need to query or a \"container\" of some data. A tabular expression statement consists zero or more operators applied in sequence. Operators are connected by a pipe (|), allowing data to flow from one operator to the next for filtering or manipulation. This sequential piping of information makes the query's operator order crucial.\n\n\nArguments\n---------\n  [MaxNoOfAggregatedEvents]\n  The maximum number of events to aggregate. After reaching this limit, aggregation stops, and all of the input events are enriched with the same, most recent aggregation results. Default: 50000.\n\n  [AggregatedField]\n  Optional name for a field that contains an aggregation result. Defaults to a name derived from the corresponding AggregationFunction.\n\n  [GroupField]\n  Optional name for a group field. Defaults to a name derived from the corresponding GroupingExpression.\n\n  [AggregationFunction]\n  A Cribl or statistical function, with field names as arguments. You can add multiple functions, separated by a comma.\n\n  [GroupingExpression]\n  The expression that groups the input events before aggregating them. You can add multiple expressions, separated by a comma.\n\n  [Scope]\n  The events to search.\n\n  [Expression]\n  A calculation over the fields of the input events.\n\n  [FieldName]\n  The name of the field to be created or modified.\n\n  [IPField]\n  The field name with an IP address. Defaults to ip.\n\n  [NewFieldName]\n  The new field name.\n\n  [ExistingFieldName]\n  The name of the existing field to rename.\n\nUse Case: EXTRACT\n==============================\n  [Description]\n  Extracting and parsing data into separate fields\n\n  [Operators]\n    [extract]\n    [description]\n  extract and parse information into separate fields (which defaults to _raw), using either a predefined Parser or various type options (such as delimited, regex, kvp, json, csv, elff, or clf)\n\n  [syntax]\n  | extract [ SourceOption ] [ type=Type | parser=Parser ] [ type=delimited [ DelimOption ] FieldList ] [ [ type=regex ] [ RegexOption ] RegexLiteral [RegexLiteral[...]] ] [ type=keyvalue [ FieldList ]] [ type=json [ FieldList ]] [ type=csv FieldList ] [ type=elff FieldList ] [ type=clf [ FieldList ]]\n\n  [arguments]\n  {\n  \"sourceOption\": \"Syntax – [ SourceIdent=FieldName ]. Defaults to source=_raw. SourceIdent: Define as source, sourceField, or src.\",\n  \"type\": \"Define as either type or format. Delimiter: delimited, del, or delim. Regex: regex, regexp, or re. Key Value: kvp, keyvalue, or kv. JSON: json or js. CSV: csv. ELF: elff or extended. CLF: clf or common (case insensitive).\",\n  \"fieldList\": \"Syntax – \\\"FieldName\\\" [, \\\"FieldNameList\\\" ]. Case sensitive. Example: \\\"field1,field2\\\". FieldIdent: Define as either field or fields. FieldNameList: Syntax – FieldName [, FieldNameList ]. Case sensitive.\",\n  \"parser\": \"Syntax – parser=\\\"KnownParserName\\\". Use a predefined Parser. Case sensitive.\"\n}\n\n  [rules]\n  The type can be automatically detected based on whether RegexLiteral or DelimOption is defined. For example, if RegexLiteral is provided, it's assigned as type=regex. Or, if DelimOption is specified, it's assigned as type=delimited.\nYou can have multiple FieldLists. These will be merged into one, larger field list.\nA FieldList is optional for the key value, JSON, and CLF types. If no FieldList is specified:\nKey value and JSON types extract all fields.\nCLF extracts clientip, ident, user, timestamp, request, status, and bytes.\nYou can define either DelimOption or RegexOption, not both.\n\n  [example]\n  dataset=myDataset | extract source=foobar type=csv \"field1,field2,field3\"\n\n  [exampleWithParser]\n  | extract parser=\"AWS VPC Flow Logs\"\n\n  [types]\n  {\n  \"delimited\": \"Extract from delimited text (CSV-like)\",\n  \"regex\": \"Extract using regular expressions\",\n  \"keyvalue\": \"Extract key-value pairs\",\n  \"json\": \"Extract from JSON\",\n  \"csv\": \"Extract from CSV format\",\n  \"elff\": \"Extract from Extended Log File Format\",\n  \"clf\": \"Extract from Common Log Format\"\n}\n\nAdditional KQL Rules\n--------------------\n- You'll be given a user prompt and potentially information about available datasets. Sometimes, you'll also be given an Invalid query and an Error message from the parser.\n- If datasets have been provided, your query should ONLY use the datasets listed.\n- If lookup tables have been provided, and they contain relevant information to the user prompt, use the lookups operator to enrich the query with the lookup table.\n- If field descriptions have been provided, your query should ONLY use the available fields from the field descriptions.\n- If you need to select multiple datasets, use the * operator. (e.g. http* will select all datasets that start with http)\n- If you need to hardcode recent dates in a query, consider the following to be today's date: 2026-04-12\n- If you don't know how to fix or generate the query, return an empty query, like {\"Valid Query\": \"\"}\n- If you need to use regex, remember that the regex must be in JavaScript syntax.\n- When the request implies time-based aggregation (e.g., \"over time\", \"grouped by hour/day\", or use of timestats), include the time grouping explicitly using 'by _time' with timestats, or use summarize + bin(_time, <span>).\n- When a user specifies an explicit time range with a timezone (e.g., \"11 AM to 12 PM PDT today\"), convert that range to UTC and use absolute earliest/latest times (e.g., earliest=18:00 latest=19:00). Prefer absolute times over relative spans in these cases.\n- Cribl Search performs automatic type conversion, giving priority to number comparisons. This works in WHERE comparisons (e.g., 'where bytes > 500'), aggregations (e.g., 'sum(bytes)'), and arithmetic operations (e.g., 'end - start'), even when fields are strings. This is a Cribl-specific extension - standard KQL requires explicit type conversion with toint(), tolong(), etc.\n- When referencing aggregate function results in subsequent clauses (like sort), use the correct default field names: count() produces 'count_', avg(fieldname) produces 'avg_fieldname', sum(bytes) produces 'sum_bytes', etc.\n- Generate complete queries with all requested operations. If the user asks for sorting (e.g., \"sort by average\", \"highest values\", \"descending\"), include the complete sort clause at the end. Multi-clause queries should include all clauses: where, summarize, additional where filters, and sort.\n- When filtering for specific log levels (e.g., \"errors\", \"warnings\"), use only the requested level without adding extra conditions like HTTP status codes. \"Errors\" means level=='error', not level=='error' or status==500. Keep filtering precise and avoid over-specification.\n- Important distinction between 'dedup' and 'distinct' operators: Use 'dedup' to remove duplicate events/rows based on field values (e.g., '| dedup by user_id'). Use 'distinct' to retrieve unique field values (e.g., '| distinct host, port'). Note: 'distinct' attempts to flatten/project fields before evaluating uniqueness. If a field doesn't exist, is null, or has inconsistent types (e.g., object vs string) across records, 'distinct' will yield null for those entries. For nested fields like 'attributes.actor.email', prefer using 'summarize' with grouping (e.g., '| summarize count() by attributes.actor.email') or 'dedup' if structural inconsistencies are expected.\n\nAssistant Constraints\n---------------------\n\nIMPORTANT: Follow these constraints strictly.\n- Call fetch_local_context on the FIRST turn of the conversation. On subsequent turns, generally use the context already in conversation history, but you may call fetch_local_context again if needed.\n- When datasets are empty, the system provides SAMPLE_DATASETS automatically.\n- ALL queries MUST start with 'cribl dataset=<name>' prefix. Never omit the 'cribl' keyword.\n- For string concatenation, you can use either the + operator (more convenient) or strcat() function. Examples: field1 + ':' + field2 OR strcat(field1, ':', field2). When concatenating values that might be numeric, prefer strcat() to avoid numeric addition.\n- If the query is invalid, you may retry the query generation twice.\n- You can invoke the validate_kql tool as many times as needed to ensure the query is valid.\n- If you don't know how to fix or generate the query, return an empty query.\n\n\n[CollectionName]\nquery_modification\n\n[CollectionDescription]\nKQL examples and syntax documentation for query_modification use case. Includes query examples and relevant operators, functions, and syntax patterns for query_modification operations.\n\n[CollectionContent]\nFew-Shot Examples\n==================\nCurrent KQL Query: cribl dataset=cribl_internal_logs datatype=cribl_json earliest=-1w@w | limit 100\nUser Prompt: extend this to 2 weeks\nDataset Information: [{\"id\":\"cribl_internal_logs\",\"provider\":\"cribl_leader\",\"description\":\"Search Cribl internal logs\"},{\"id\":\"cribl_edge_appscope_metrics\",\"provider\":\"cribl_edge\",\"description\":\"Search Appscope metrics across all Cribl Edge fleets\"}]\nGenerated KQL Query: cribl dataset=cribl_internal_logs datatype=cribl_json earliest=-2w@w | limit 100\n\n---\n\n\nKQL Syntax Documentation\n=========================\n\nBasics of Cribl Syntax\n----------------------\nThe Cribl Search Query Language is based on Microsoft's Kusto Query Language (KQL). A Cribl Search Query is a read-only request expressed in plain text that processes data and returns results in a tabular or graphical format. It consists of one or more query statements. Predominant type of query statement in a tabular expression statement. In a tabular expression statement, both input and output consists of tables or datasets. Think of a dataset as a definition that describes WHAT we need to query or a \"container\" of some data. A tabular expression statement consists zero or more operators applied in sequence. Operators are connected by a pipe (|), allowing data to flow from one operator to the next for filtering or manipulation. This sequential piping of information makes the query's operator order crucial.\n\n\nArguments\n---------\n  [MaxNoOfAggregatedEvents]\n  The maximum number of events to aggregate. After reaching this limit, aggregation stops, and all of the input events are enriched with the same, most recent aggregation results. Default: 50000.\n\n  [AggregatedField]\n  Optional name for a field that contains an aggregation result. Defaults to a name derived from the corresponding AggregationFunction.\n\n  [GroupField]\n  Optional name for a group field. Defaults to a name derived from the corresponding GroupingExpression.\n\n  [AggregationFunction]\n  A Cribl or statistical function, with field names as arguments. You can add multiple functions, separated by a comma.\n\n  [GroupingExpression]\n  The expression that groups the input events before aggregating them. You can add multiple expressions, separated by a comma.\n\n  [Scope]\n  The events to search.\n\n  [Expression]\n  A calculation over the fields of the input events.\n\n  [FieldName]\n  The name of the field to be created or modified.\n\n  [IPField]\n  The field name with an IP address. Defaults to ip.\n\n  [NewFieldName]\n  The new field name.\n\n  [ExistingFieldName]\n  The name of the existing field to rename.\n\nUse Case: QUERY_MODIFICATION\n==============================\n  [Description]\n  Modifying and controlling query execution and results\n\n  [Operators]\n    [limit]\n    [description]\n  returns up to the specified number of events (take and limit are synonyms)\n\n  [syntax]\n  | limit NumberOfEvents\n\n  [example]\n  | limit 10\n\n  [take]\n    [description]\n  limits the number of events (same as limit).\n\n  [syntax]\n  Scope | take NumberOfEvents\n\n  [example]\n  dataset=myDataset | take 10\n\n  [top]\n    [description]\n  returns the first N events sorted by the specified fields.\n\n  [syntax]\n  Scope | top NumberOfEvents [ by Field [ asc | desc ] [ nulls first | nulls last ] [, ...] ]\n\n  [example]\n  dataset=myDataset | top 10 by timestamp asc\n\n  [sort]\n    [description]\n  arranges events into order by one or more fields (same as order).\n\n  [syntax]\n  Scope | sort [ topN=MaxNoOfOutputEvents ] [ maxEvents=MaxNoOfInputEvents ] by Field [ asc | desc ] [ nulls first | nulls last ] [, ...]\n\n  [example]\n  dataset=myDataset | sort by timestamp asc\n\n  [order]\n    [description]\n  arranges events into order by one or more fields (same as sort)\n\n  [syntax]\n  Scope | order [ topN=MaxNoOfOutputEvents ] [ maxEvents=MaxNoOfInputEvents ] by Field [ asc | desc ] [ nulls first | nulls last ] [, ...]\n\n  [example]\n  dataset=myDataset | order by timestamp asc\n\n  [project-away]\n    [description]\n  excludes specific fields from the results\n\n  [syntax]\n  Scope | project-away FieldName [, ...]\n\n  [example]\n  dataset=myDataset | project-away myField, myOtherField\n\n  [centralize]\n    [description]\n  The centralize operator enforces the execution of operators on the coordinator rather than federated executors. This is useful where executors lack network visibility to the destination.\n\n  [render]\n    [description]\n  enforces a specific visualization of the search results. Options are 'event' and 'table'.\n\n  [syntax]\n  | render\n\n  [example]\n  | render\n\n  [queryStructure]\n  {\n  \"basicQuery\": \"cribl dataset=<dataset_name> [time_filters] | [operators]\",\n  \"subqueries\": \"let SubqueryName = Subquery;\\nMainQuery | [operators]\",\n  \"multipleOperators\": \"Operators are connected by a pipe (|), allowing data to flow from one operator to the next\",\n  \"operatorOrder\": \"The query's operator order is crucial - data flows sequentially through operators\"\n}\n\nAdditional KQL Rules\n--------------------\n- You'll be given a user prompt and potentially information about available datasets. Sometimes, you'll also be given an Invalid query and an Error message from the parser.\n- If datasets have been provided, your query should ONLY use the datasets listed.\n- If lookup tables have been provided, and they contain relevant information to the user prompt, use the lookups operator to enrich the query with the lookup table.\n- If field descriptions have been provided, your query should ONLY use the available fields from the field descriptions.\n- If you need to select multiple datasets, use the * operator. (e.g. http* will select all datasets that start with http)\n- If you need to hardcode recent dates in a query, consider the following to be today's date: 2026-04-12\n- If you don't know how to fix or generate the query, return an empty query, like {\"Valid Query\": \"\"}\n- If you need to use regex, remember that the regex must be in JavaScript syntax.\n- When the request implies time-based aggregation (e.g., \"over time\", \"grouped by hour/day\", or use of timestats), include the time grouping explicitly using 'by _time' with timestats, or use summarize + bin(_time, <span>).\n- When a user specifies an explicit time range with a timezone (e.g., \"11 AM to 12 PM PDT today\"), convert that range to UTC and use absolute earliest/latest times (e.g., earliest=18:00 latest=19:00). Prefer absolute times over relative spans in these cases.\n- Cribl Search performs automatic type conversion, giving priority to number comparisons. This works in WHERE comparisons (e.g., 'where bytes > 500'), aggregations (e.g., 'sum(bytes)'), and arithmetic operations (e.g., 'end - start'), even when fields are strings. This is a Cribl-specific extension - standard KQL requires explicit type conversion with toint(), tolong(), etc.\n- When referencing aggregate function results in subsequent clauses (like sort), use the correct default field names: count() produces 'count_', avg(fieldname) produces 'avg_fieldname', sum(bytes) produces 'sum_bytes', etc.\n- Generate complete queries with all requested operations. If the user asks for sorting (e.g., \"sort by average\", \"highest values\", \"descending\"), include the complete sort clause at the end. Multi-clause queries should include all clauses: where, summarize, additional where filters, and sort.\n- When filtering for specific log levels (e.g., \"errors\", \"warnings\"), use only the requested level without adding extra conditions like HTTP status codes. \"Errors\" means level=='error', not level=='error' or status==500. Keep filtering precise and avoid over-specification.\n- Important distinction between 'dedup' and 'distinct' operators: Use 'dedup' to remove duplicate events/rows based on field values (e.g., '| dedup by user_id'). Use 'distinct' to retrieve unique field values (e.g., '| distinct host, port'). Note: 'distinct' attempts to flatten/project fields before evaluating uniqueness. If a field doesn't exist, is null, or has inconsistent types (e.g., object vs string) across records, 'distinct' will yield null for those entries. For nested fields like 'attributes.actor.email', prefer using 'summarize' with grouping (e.g., '| summarize count() by attributes.actor.email') or 'dedup' if structural inconsistencies are expected.\n\nAssistant Constraints\n---------------------\n\nIMPORTANT: Follow these constraints strictly.\n- Call fetch_local_context on the FIRST turn of the conversation. On subsequent turns, generally use the context already in conversation history, but you may call fetch_local_context again if needed.\n- When datasets are empty, the system provides SAMPLE_DATASETS automatically.\n- ALL queries MUST start with 'cribl dataset=<name>' prefix. Never omit the 'cribl' keyword.\n- For string concatenation, you can use either the + operator (more convenient) or strcat() function. Examples: field1 + ':' + field2 OR strcat(field1, ':', field2). When concatenating values that might be numeric, prefer strcat() to avoid numeric addition.\n- If the query is invalid, you may retry the query generation twice.\n- You can invoke the validate_kql tool as many times as needed to ensure the query is valid.\n- If you don't know how to fix or generate the query, return an empty query.\n","tool_call_id":"call_aBjcevkHZKPCOJGoymTwzY8V","name":"tool:fetch_local_context"}

